Visual Encounter Surveys

Load and Wrangle VES Data

\(~\)

Load data

ves <- read_csv(here("data", "ves.csv")) %>% 
  clean_names()

\(~\)

VES wrangling

visual <- ves %>% 
  group_by(site, species_ves) %>% 
  summarise(count = sum(count),
            species_ves = species_ves) %>% 
  mutate(repeat_id = cur_group_id(),
         species_ves = as.factor(species_ves)) %>% 
  filter(!duplicated(repeat_id)) %>% 
  select(!repeat_id)

visual$scaled_count<- ((visual$count/ sum(visual$count))*100) %>% 
  round(digits = 2)

\(~\)

Visualize All VES Data

ggplot(data = visual, aes(fill = species_ves, x = reorder(species_ves, -scaled_count), y = scaled_count)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_text(aes(label = scaled_count), vjust = -0.5, size = 3) +
  theme_classic()+
  facet_grid(~site) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 0.5),
        strip.background = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(name = "Species") +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0,0), limits = c(0,60)) +
  ylab("Percent Occurrence") +
  xlab("Species") +
  labs(title = "All VES Sites",
       subtitle = "n=282 counts") +
  annotate("segment",x=Inf,xend=-Inf,y=Inf,yend=Inf,color="black",lwd=0.5)

Interpretation: From this figure we can see the percent occurrence per species at each unique site from the VES. There were 5 unique sites within the VES and 3 unique species recorded in the VES. It appears Rana clamitans is the most occurring species and Rana pipiens the least occurring species in the VES.

\(~\)

VES wrangling - Tuttle Pond and Wood Lab Pond (repeated sites)

ves_repeat_survs <- ves %>% 
  group_by(site, date, species_ves) %>% 
  summarise(count = sum(count),
            species_ves = species_ves) %>% 
  mutate(repeat_id = cur_group_id()) %>% 
  filter(!duplicated(repeat_id),
         site %in% c("tuttle pond", "wood lab pond")) %>% 
  select(!repeat_id) %>% 
  mutate(site = as.factor(site),
         date = as.factor(date),
         species_ves = as.factor(species_ves))


tuttle <- ves_repeat_survs %>% 
  filter(site == "tuttle pond")

tuttle$scaled_count<- ((tuttle$count/ sum(tuttle$count))*100)


wood <- ves_repeat_survs %>% 
  filter(site == "wood lab pond")

wood$scaled_count<- ((wood$count/ sum(wood$count))*100)

\(~\)

Visualize Tuttle Pond

ggplot(data = tuttle, aes(fill = species_ves, x = fct_infreq(species_ves), y = scaled_count)) +
  geom_col() +

  theme_classic()+

        strip.background = element_blank(),

Interpretation: Tuttle Pond was one of two repeated sites, the other being Woods Lab Pond. VES for Tuttle Pond was conducted during 3 unique dates with trends eliciting the date when the survey was conducted may have an impact on the species occurrence. A total of 100 frogs were observed during those 3 dates.

\(~\)

Analyse Tuttle Pond

\(~\)

VES Analysis DF

ves_analsys_tuttle <- ves %>% 
  select(c(site, date, species_ves, count)) %>% 
  filter(site == "tuttle pond") %>% 
  mutate(site = as.factor(site),
         date = as.factor(date),
         species_ves = as.factor(species_ves))

ves_analsys_tuttle$scaled_count<- ((ves_analsys_tuttle$count/ sum(ves_analsys_tuttle$count))*100)

\(~\)

One-way ANOVA determining if date has an affect on mean percent occurrence per species at Tuttle Pond

\(~\)

H0: There is no difference in mean percent occurrence per species between the dates surveyed at Tuttle Pond
HA: There is a difference in mean percent occurrence per species between the dates surveyed at Tuttle Pond
one_way_date <- aov(scaled_count ~ date, data = ves_analsys_tuttle)

tidy(one_way_date) %>% 
  kable(digits = 2) %>% 
  kable_styling()
term df sumsq meansq statistic p.value
date 2 47.64 23.82 3.75 0.04
Residuals 28 177.78 6.35 NA NA
Interpretation: With an \(\alpha\)=0.05 we reject the null hypothesis and expect date has an affect on mean percent occurrence for Tuttle Pond.

\(~\)

One-way ANOVA determing if the species surveyed has an affect on mean percent occurrence per species at Tuttle Pond

\(~\)

H0: There is no difference in mean species count between species surveyed Tuttle Pond
HA: There is a difference in mean percent occurrence per species between species surveyed Tuttle Pond
one_way_species <- aov(scaled_count ~ species_ves, data = ves_analsys_tuttle)

tidy(one_way_species) %>% 
  kable(digits = 2) %>% 
  kable_styling()
term df sumsq meansq statistic p.value
species_ves 2 16.09 8.05 1.08 0.35
Residuals 28 209.33 7.48 NA NA
Interpretation: With an \(\alpha\)=0.05 we fail reject the null hypothesis and expect species surveyed does not affect in mean percent occurrence per species for Tuttle Pond.

\(~\)

Two-way ANOVA determining if the species surveyed and date of survey has an affect on mean percent occurrence per species at Tuttle Pond

\(~\)

H0: There is no difference in mean occurrence per species from the dates surveyed and species surveyed at Tuttle Pond
HA: There is a difference in mean occurrence per species from the dates surveyed and species surveyed at Tuttle Pond
two_way_species_date <- aov(scaled_count ~ date + species_ves, data = ves_analsys_tuttle)

tidy(two_way_species_date) %>% 
  kable(digits = 2) %>% 
  kable_styling()
term df sumsq meansq statistic p.value
date 2 47.64 23.82 3.54 0.04
species_ves 2 2.76 1.38 0.20 0.82
Residuals 26 175.03 6.73 NA NA

Analyse Sites

\(~\)

One-way ANOVA/T-test determining if site has an affect on mean percent occurrence per species

\(~\)

H0: There is no difference on mean percent occurrence per species between repeated sites (Tuttle & Wood)
HA: There is a difference in mean percent occurrence per species between repeated sites (Tuttle & Wood)
one_way_site <- aov(scaled_count ~ site, data = combine_analysis)
tidy(one_way_site) %>% 
  kable(digits = 4) %>% 
  kable_styling()
term df sumsq meansq statistic p.value
site 1 27.7319 27.7319 5.888 0.02
Residuals 39 183.6859 4.7099 NA NA
Interpretation: With an \(\alpha\)=0.05 we reject the null and expect the site that has been repeated for a VES will affect the mean percent occurance per species.

\(~\)

One-way ANOVA determining if species has an affect on mean percent occurrence per species

\(~\)

H0: There is no difference in mean species counts between species surveyed at repeated sites (Tuttle & Wood)
HA: There is a difference in mean species counts between species surveyed repeated sites (Tuttle & Wood)
one_way_spec <- aov(scaled_count ~ species_ves, data = combine_analysis)
tidy(one_way_spec) %>% 
  kable(digits = 4) %>% 
  kable_styling()
term df sumsq meansq statistic p.value
species_ves 2 9.1764 4.5882 0.8621 0.4304
Residuals 38 202.2414 5.3221 NA NA
Interpretation: With an \(\alpha\)=0.05 we fail to reject the null and see no difference in percent occurance between each species for sites repeated for VES.

two_way_site_species <- aov(scaled_count ~ site + species_ves, data = combine_analysis)

Capture & Visual Encounter Surveys

\(~\)

Load and Wrangle Capture Data

\(~\)

Load data

cap <- read_csv(here("data", "cap.csv")) %>% 
  clean_names()

\(~\)

Wrangle Capture data and join with VES data

capture <- cap %>% 
  mutate(count = 1) %>% 
  group_by(site, species_capture) %>% 
  summarise(count = sum(count),
            species_capture = species_capture) %>% 
  mutate(repeat_id = cur_group_id(),
         species_capture = str_replace(species_capture, "possibly", ""),
         species_capture = str_replace(species_capture, "[[:punct:]]", "")) %>% 
  filter(!duplicated(repeat_id)) %>% 
  filter(!species_capture == "negative control") %>% 
  select(!repeat_id) %>% 
  rename(capture_count = count) %>% 
  mutate(species_capture = as.factor(species_capture))

capture$capture_scaled_count<- ((capture$capture_count/ sum(capture$capture_count))*100) %>% 
  round(digits = 2)

visual_join <- visual %>% 
  rename(visual_count = count,
         visual_scaled_count = scaled_count)

comb_data <- merge(capture, visual_join, by.x = c("site", "species_capture"), by.y = c("site", "species_ves")) %>% 
  rename(species = species_capture) %>% 
  select(!c(capture_count, visual_count)) %>% 
  pivot_longer(!c(site, species), names_to = "capture_ves", values_to = "scaled_count") %>% 
  mutate(species = as.factor(species))

\(~\)

Visualize All Capture Data

ggplot(data = capture, aes(x = reorder(species_capture, -capture_scaled_count), 
                           y = capture_scaled_count, 
                           fill = species_capture)) +
  geom_col(stat = 'identity') +
  theme_classic()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5),
        strip.background = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(name = "Species") +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0,0), limits = c(0,30)) +
  ylab("Percent Captured") +
  xlab("Species") +
  labs(title = "All Capture Data")

Interpretation: Of all the Capture Survey data, when looking at similiar species from VES, we see Rana catesbeiana being captured the most, Rana clamitans captured the second most, and Rana pipiens being captured the 5th most.

\(~\)

Visualize Capture and VES Data for Matching Sites and Species

ggplot(data = comb_data, aes(x = reorder(species, -scaled_count), y = scaled_count, fill = capture_ves)) +
  geom_col(stat = "identity", position = position_dodge()) +
  theme_classic()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 0.5),
        strip.background = element_blank()) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(name = "Survey Method") +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0,0), limits = c(0,35)) +
  ylab("Percent Occurrence") +
  xlab("Species") +
  labs(title = "Capture and VES Species Occurance",
       subtitle = "Matching Sites and Species")

Interpretation: When comparing the percent occurrence between the 3 similiar species, 2 different survey types (Capture Surveys and VES), and sites where both occured, we see similiar percent occurrences for Rana catesbeiana and Rana pipiens and starkly different percent occurrences in Rana clamitans.

Analyse Capture and VES data

\(~\)

One-way ANOVA/T-test determining if the survey method affects the mean percent occurrence per species

\(~\)

H0: There is no difference in mean percent occurrence per species between survey methods (Capture & VES)
HA: There is a difference in mean percent occurrence per species between survey methods (Capture & VES)
cap_ves <- aov(scaled_count ~ capture_ves, data = comb_data)
tidy(cap_ves) %>% 
  kable(digits = 4) %>% 
  kable_styling()
term df sumsq meansq statistic p.value
capture_ves 1 74.8148 74.8148 0.8956 0.3553
Residuals 20 1670.7209 83.5360 NA NA
Interpretation: With an \(\alpha\)=0.05 we fail to reject the null indicating there is no difference in percent occurance per species between survey methods.
